        <bioghist id="ref2">
            <head>Biographical/Historical note</head>
            <p>Willie J. Macon was drafted into the U.S. Army at the age of 19. He went to Camp Upton in Long Island, NY for basic training. From there he was shipped to California, and then Manila. He worked for the Quartermaster Corps, and was in charge of trucking supplies, such as food and clothing, to the troops in the Philippines. The U.S. Army was mostly segregated at the time, therefore Macon's unit was entirely African American with a white commanding officer. Macon had a variety of experiences while in the army, including seeking the Army's permission to marry a Phillippine woman, having the truck he was driving bombed by the Japanese, and training a champion army boxer. Macon was discharged in February of 1946 and went to New York City, where he lived for a time. He also lived in Washington, D.C. before moving to Connecticut.</p>
        </bioghist>
